The age group distribution differed significantly between males and females, with a higher-than-predicted proportion of men and a lower-than-predicted proportion of females being aged ≥80 years (Chi-square statistic = 16.07; P
 = 0.003) (Table 4
).

To determine if there was any variation in sensitivity and specificity of detection according to age of the patient from whom the sample was taken, the group was divided into age groups (Table 1, Table 5
). The sensitivity of the Cepheid® Xpert Flu Assay for detection of H1N1 by comparison to the gold standard method was 100% for the 0–19-year group. Sensitivity was lower for older age groups (Table 5), but the variation across age groups in distribution of true-positive samples for H1N1 versus samples which were positive for the MOH method and negative for the Xpert method was not statistically significant (Chi-square statistic = 5.76; P
 = 0.22). Specificity for H1N1 detection remained uniformly high across age groups (Table 5).
